{{EU-stub}}

The '''Experimental Music Studios''' (EMS) is an organization or center for [[electroacoustic music|electroacoustic]] and [[computer music]], focusing on [[sound synthesis|synthesis]] and [[concert]] performance of [[art music]],<ref name="EMS">"[http://ems.music.illinois.edu/ems the Experimental Music Studios]", ''EMS.music.Illinois.edu''. Accessed: February 26, 2017</ref> founded by [[Lejaren Hiller]] at [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]] in 1958.
The "second electronic music studio developed in the United States",<ref name="Bohn">[[James Bohn|Bohn, James]] (undated). "[http://ems.music.illinois.edu/ems/history/ems Early History of the Experimental Music Studios]", ''EMS.music.Illinois.edu''. Accessed: February 26, 2017.</ref> and the "first formally acknowledged electro-acoustic facility in the United States" (since the [[Computer Music Center|Columbia-Princeton Electronic Music Center]], "although formally acknowledged in 1959, {{sic|had began}} in 1952"<ref name="Battisti">Battisti, Emanuele (undated). "[http://ems.music.illinois.edu/ems/articles/battisti The Experimental Music Studio at the University of Illinois, 1958-68]", ''EMS.music.Illinois.edu''. Accessed: February 26, 2017.</ref>) at an initial cost of $8,000, early equipment included an "old broadcasting studio control panel" as console, microphones, amplifiers, oscilloscopes, tape decks, and other donated items.<ref name="Bohn"/> The studios received a $30,000 grant from [[Magnavox]] in 1962,<ref name="Slide"/> and a $53,100 grant from the [[National Science Foundation]] in 1965.<ref name="Battisti"/> Directed by [[Scott_A._Wyatt]] for forty years, it is currently directed by [[Eli Fieldsteel]],<ref name="EMS"/> and consists of multiple studios.<ref>Fieldsteel, Eli (undated). "[https://music.illinois.edu/experimental-music-studios Experimental Music Studios]", ''Music.Illinois.edu''. Accessed: February 26, 2017.</ref><ref>"[http://ems.music.illinois.edu/ Welcome to the Experimental Music Studios of the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]", ''EMS.music.Illinois.edu''. Accessed: February 26, 2017.</ref>
Alumni include [[Adrian Belew]], [[Neely Bruce]], [[Herbert Brün]], [[Mary Ellen Childs]], [[Insook Choi]], [[Donnacha Dennehy]], [[Robert Fleisher]], [[Mara Helmuth]], [[Elizabeth Hinkle-Turner]], [[Ben Johnston (composer)|Ben Johnston]], [[Salvatore Martirano]], [[Larry Polansky]], [[David Rosenboom]], [[Carla Scaletti]], [[James Tenney]], [[David Ward-Steinman]], [[David Weinstein (musician)|David Weinstein]], and [[Olly Wilson]].<ref>"[http://ems.music.illinois.edu/personnel/ems/alumni Experimental Music Studios Alumni]", ''EMS.music.Illinois.edu''. Accessed: February 26, 2017.</ref> Composers who worked at the center between 1958 and 1975 include [[John Cage]], [[Michael Colgrass]], [[Kenneth Gaburo]], [[Charles Hamm]], and [[John Melby]].<ref name="Slide">"[http://ems.music.illinois.edu/ems/ems-history EMS History Slide Show]" (slides 3<!--composers--> and 15<!--Non Sequitur VI-->), ''EMS.music.Illinois.edu''. Accessed: February 26, 2017.</ref>
Hiller created the '''MUSICOMP''' ("MUsic SImulator-Interpreter for COMpositional Procedures") [[programming language]] for music composition with Robert Baker in order to create their ''Computer Cantata'' (1963) at the studios.<ref>Bohn, James (undated). "[http://ems.music.illinois.edu/ems/history/hiller Lejaren Hiller]", ''ems.music.illinois.edu''. Accessed: February 26, 2017.</ref> MUSICOMP was used by Brün in generating his ''Non Sequitur VI'' (1966).<ref name="Slide"/> Composer [[James Beauchamp]] developed the '''Harmonic Tone Generator''' (a form of [[additive synthesis]]) at the studios.<ref name="Slide"/>
