{{History of Croatia}}
The origin of the [[Croats]] before the [[Migration Period|great migration]] of the Slavs is uncertain. The modern Croats are considered a [[Slavs|Slavic]] people, but the archaeological and other historic evidence on the migration of the Slavic settlers, the character of native population on present-day territory of Croatia, and their mutual relationship show diverse historical influences.

==Croatian ethnogenesis==
The definition of Croatian [[ethnogenesis]] begins with the definition of [[Ethnic group|ethnicity]],{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=251}} according to which an ethnic group is a socially defined category of people who identify with each other based on common ancestral, social, cultural or other experience, and which shows a certain durability over the long period term of time.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=251-252}} In the Croatian case, there's no doubt that in the [[Early Middle Ages]] a certain group identified themselves by ethnonym ''Hrvati'' (Croats), and was identified as such by the others.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=252}} It also had a political connotation, it continued to expand, and since the [[Late Middle Ages]] explicitly identified with the [[nation]], although not in the exact meaning as of the contemporary modern nation.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=252}}

In the case of the present-day Croatian nation it could be said that several components or phases influenced its ethnogenesis:

* the indigenous [[Prehistory|prehistoric]] component which dates from Stone Age, before 40,000 years, and the younger [[Neolithic]] culture like [[Danilo culture|Danilo]] dated 4700-3900 BC, and [[Chalcolithic|Eneolithic]] culture like [[Vučedol culture|Vučedol]] dated 3000 and 2200 BC.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=253}}
* the [[Protohistory|protohistoric]] component, which includes ancient people like [[Illyrians]] (including the [[Dalmatae]] and [[Liburnians]] in coastal Croatia, and the [[List of ancient tribes in Illyria#Pannonian tribes|Pannonii]] in continental Croatia); [[Celts#Eastward expansion|Celtic]] or mixed Celtic-Illyrian people, such as the [[Iapydes]], [[Taurisci]] and [[Scordisci]] also existed for a time in continental Croatia.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=253}} In the 4th century BCE there also existed a few Greek colonies on the Adriatic islands and coast.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=253}}
* the [[Classical antiquity#Roman Republic (5th to 1st centuries BC)|classical antiquity]] component caused by the Roman conquest, which included a mixture of ancient [[Illyrian people]] and Rome's [[Colonia (Roman)|colonists]] and [[Legionary|legionaries]];{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=253-254}} there was also a temporary presence of Iranian-speaking [[Iazyges]] on the border of Roman [[Dalmatia (Roman province)|Dalmatia]] at this time.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=256}}
* the [[Late Antiquity]]-[[Early Middle Ages]] component from the [[Migration Period]], started by the [[Huns]], and which in Croatia included in the first phase [[Visigoths]] and [[Suebi]], who didn't stay for a long period of time, and [[Ostrogoths]], [[Gepids]] and [[Lombards|Langobards]], who formed the brief [[Ostrogothic Kingdom]] (493-553 AD).{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=254}} In the second phase occurred the great [[Slavs|Slav]] migration, often associated with the [[Avars (Carpathians)|Avars]]' activity.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=254}} A large part of the agricultural population of Dalmatia at the time was descendent from Vlachs or Morlachs, a formerly Latin-speaking population.<ref>Stanko Guldescu, The Croatian-Slavonian Kingdom: 1526-1792, Walter de Gruyter GmbH & Co KG, 1970, p.70, {{ISBN|9783110881622}}</ref>
* the final [[Middle Ages]]-[[Early modern Europe|Modern Age]] component, which included the presence of [[Magyars]]/[[Hungarians]], [[Italians]]/[[Republic of Venice|Venetians]], and [[Germans]]/[[Saxons]].{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=254}} After the 14th century, because of the [[black death]], and the late 15th century, because of [[Hundred Years' Croatian–Ottoman War|Ottoman invasion]], the Croatian ethnonym expanded from the historic Croatian lands to Western Slavonia, which caused [[Zagreb]] to become capital city of the Croatian Kingdom, and to become incorporated with the population ethnogenesis of that territory.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=254}} The Ottoman invasion caused many migrations of the people in the Balkans and in Croatia, like those of the [[Vlachs of Croatia|Vlachs]],{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=254-255}} but the upcoming world wars and social events also influenced the Croatian ethnogenesis.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=254-255}}

===Old historical sources===
[[File:Oton Ivekovic, Dolazak Hrvata na Jadran.jpg|thumb|right|''The Coming of the Croats to the Adriatic'' (1905) by [[Oton Iveković]]]]
The mention of the [[Name of Croatia#Etymology|Croatian ethnonym]] ''Hrvat'' for a specific tribe before the 9th century is not yet completely confirmed. According to [[Constantine VII]]'s work ''[[De Administrando Imperio]]'' (10th century), a group of Croats separated from the [[White Croats]] who lived in [[White Croatia]] and arrived by their own will, or were called by the Byzantine Emperor [[Heraclius]] (610-641), to [[Dalmatia (Roman province)|Dalmatia]] where they fought and defeated the Avars, and eventually organized their own [[Duchy of Croatia|principality]].{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=258}} According to the legend preserved in the work, they were led by five brothers ''Κλουκας'' (Kloukas), ''Λόβελος'' (Lobelos), ''Κοσέντζης'' (Kosentzis), ''Μουχλώ'' (Mouchlo), ''Χρωβάτος'' (Chrobatos), and two sisters ''Τουγά'' (Touga) and ''Βουγά'' (Bouga),{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=258}}{{sfn|Živković|2012|p=113}} and their archon at the time was ''father'' of [[Porga of Croatia|Porga]], and they were baptized during the rule of Porga in the 7th century.{{sfn|Živković|2012|p=54-56, 140}}

The old historical sources do not give an exact indication of the ethnogenesis of these early Croats. Constantine VII does not identify Croats with Slavs, nor does he point to differences between them.<ref>{{cite book |last= Goldstein |first= Ivo |author-link= Ivo Goldstein |date= 1995 |title= Hrvatski rani srednji vijek |trans-title= Croatian Early Middle Age |language= Croatian |publisher= Novi Liber |location= Zagreb |pages= 23 |isbn= 953-6045-02-8}}</ref> [[John Skylitzes]] in his work ''[[Madrid Skylitzes]]'' [[c:File:Delegation of Croats and Serbs to Emperor Basil I, Skylitzes.jpg|identified]] Croats and Serbs as [[Scythians]]. [[Nestor the Chronicler]] in his ''[[Primary Chronicle]]'' identified White Croats with West Slavs along [[Vistula]] river, with other Croats included in the East Slavic tribal union. The ''[[Chronicle of the Priest of Duklja]]'' identifies Croats with the Goths who remained after king [[Totila]] occupied the province of Dalmatia.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=259}} Similarly, [[Thomas the Archdeacon]] in his work ''[[Historia Salonitana]]'' mentions that seven or eight tribes of nobles, which he called "Lingones", arrived from present-day [[Poland]] and settled in Croatia under Totila's leadership.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=259}}

==Research history==
The Croatian ethnonym ''Hrvat'', as well of those five brothers and sisters and the early ruler Porga, are not considered to be of Slavic origin, yet again, are quite original to be a pure fabrication of Constantine VII.{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=20}}{{sfn|Živković|2012|p=54-55, 114-115}} As such, the origin of the early Croats before and at the time of arrival to the present day Croatia, as well their ethnonym, were an eternal topic of historiography, linguistics and archeology.{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=20}} However, the theories were often elaborated in non-scientific terms, supported by specific ideological intentions, and often by political and cultural intentions of the time.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=260-262}} This kind of interpretations caused a lot of damage to certain theories and actual scientific community.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=260-262}} It should be taken into serious consideration whether the origin of the early Croatian tribes can be regarded also as the origin of Croatian nation, and can only be asserted that the Croats as are known today as a nation became only when Croatian tribes arrived in the territory of present-day Croatia.{{sfn|Katičić|1999|p=15-16}}

===Slavic theory===
The Slavic, also known as Pan-Slavic and Autochthonous-Slavic theory, dates back to the [[Renaissance in Croatia|Croatian Renaissance]], when was supported by [[Vinko Pribojević]] and [[Juraj Šižgorić]].{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=259}} There's no doubt that [[Croatian language]] belongs to the Slavic languages, but they considered that Slavs were autochthonous in [[Illyricum (Roman province)|Illyricum]] and their ancestors were old Illyrians.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=259}} It developed among the Dalmatian humanists,{{sfn|Džino|2010|p=17}} and was also considered by early modern writers, like [[Matija Petar Katančić]], [[Mavro Orbini]] and [[Pavao Ritter Vitezović]].{{sfn|Džino|2010|p=17}} This cultural and [[Croatian literature#Age of Enlightenment, Humanism, Romanticism and the Croatian National Revival|romanticist]] idea was especially promoted by the national [[Illyrian Movement]] and their leader [[Ljudevit Gaj]] in the 19th century.{{sfn|Džino|2010|p=17}}

With the development of Croatian historiography, since the 17th century, the Slavic theory was elaborated in more realistic terms, and considered Croats as one of the Slavic groups which settled in their modern-day homeland during the migration period.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=259}} Constantine the VII's work was particularly researched by the 17th century historian [[Johannes Lucius|Ivan Lučić]],{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=259}}{{sfn|Džino|2010|p=18}} who concluded that the Croats came from White Croatia on the other side of the [[Carpathian Mountains|Carpathian mountains]], in "[[Sarmatism|Sarmatia]]" (Poland), with which historians today agree upon.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=259}} The autochthonous idea, that the Slavs came to Illyricum from Poland is of even older origin (12th century).{{sfn|Džino|2010|p=17}}

In the late 19th century, the most significant impact on the future historiography had [[Franjo Rački]], and the intellectual and political circle around [[Josip Juraj Strossmayer]].{{sfn|Džino|2010|p=18}} Rački's view of the unified arrival of the Croats and Serbs to the "partially empty house",{{sfn|Džino|2010|p=18–19}} fit the ideological [[Yugoslavism]] and [[Pan-Slavism]].{{sfn|Džino|2010|p=18–19}} The ideas by Rački were furtherly developed by historian [[Ferdo Šišić]] in his seminal work ''History of the Croats in the Age of the Croat Rulers'' (1925).{{sfn|Džino|2010|p=19}} The work is considered as the foundation stone for later historiography.{{sfn|Džino|2010|p=19}} However, in the [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia|first]] and [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|second]] [[Yugoslavia]], the Pan-Slavic (pure-Slavic) theory was particularly emphasized because of the political context and was the only officially accepted theory by the regime,{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=259, 261}}{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=27}}{{sfn|Bartulin|2013|p=224}} while others which attributed non-Slavic origin and components were ignored and not accepted,{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=27}}{{sfn|Bartulin|2013|p=224}} and even their supporters, because of also political reasons, were persecuted ([[Milan Šufflay]], Kerubin Šegvić, [[Ivo Pilar]] and Mihovil Lovrić).<ref>{{cite news |last=Stagličić |first=Ivan |date=23 November 2010 |title=Gdje su Hrvati disali prije "stoljeća sedmog"? |trans-title=Where did Croats breath before "seventh century"? |url=http://www.zadarskilist.hr/clanci/23112010/gdje-su-hrvati-disali-prije-stoljeca-sedmog |language=Croatian |newspaper=[[Zadarski list]] |location=Zadar |access-date=15 March 2015}}</ref>{{sfn|Bartulin|2013|p=224}} The official theory also ignored some historical sources, like the account of Constantine VII, and considered that the Croats and Serbs were the same Slavic people who arrived in one and the same migration, and unwilling to consider foreign elements in those separate societies.<ref name="Fine">{{cite book |author=John Van Antwerp Fine |author-link=John Van Antwerp Fine, Jr. |title=The Early Medieval Balkans: A Critical Survey from the Sixth to the Late Twelfth Century |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y0NBxG9Id58C |publisher=University of Michigan Press |year=1991 |pages=53, 56–57 |isbn=9780472081493}}</ref> There were Yugoslavian scholars like Ferdo Šišić and [[Nada Klaić]] who allowed limited non-Slavic origin of certain elements in Croatian ethnogenesis, and they were usually connected with the Avars and Bulgars.{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=27}}{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=261}} One of the main difficulties with the Pan-Slavic theory was the Croatian (and Serbian) ethnonym which could not be derived from the Slavic language.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=259}}

According to the ''autochthonous model'', the Slavs homeland was in the area of former Yugoslavia, and they spread northwards and westwards rather than the other way round.<ref name="Katičić">{{citation |last=Katičić |first=Radoslav |date=1991 |title=Ivan Mužić o podrijetlu Hrvata |trans-title=Ivan Mužić about origin of Croats |url=http://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=140541&lang=en |language=Croatian |journal=Starohrvatska prosvjeta |volume=III |issue=19 |pages=250, 255–259}}</ref> A revision of the theory, developed by Ivan Mužić, argues that Slavic migration from the north did happen, but the actual number of Slavic settlers was small and that the autochthonous ethnic substratum was prevalent in the formation of the Croats, but that contradicts and doesn't answer the presence of predominant Slavic language.<ref name="Katičić"/>{{sfn|Džino|2010|p=17}} The social and linguistical situation that made the pre-Slavic population is hard to reconstruct, especially if is accepted the theory that the autochthonous population was dominant at the time of arrival of the Slavs yet accepted the language and culture of Slavic newcomers who were in the minority.{{sfn|Matasović|2008|p=46}} This scenario can only be explained with the possible distortion of the cultural and ethnic identity of the native Romanized population that happened after the fall of West Roman Empire, and that the new Slavic language and culture was seen as a prestigious idiom they had to, or wanted to accept.{{sfn|Matasović|2008|p=46}} The assumptions that the Illyrians were an ethnolinguistic homogeneous entity were rejected in the 20th century, and according to the scholars who support the ''Danube basin hypothesis'' of the [[Slavs#Homeland|Slavic homeland]], it is considered that some proto-Slavic tribes existed even before the Slavic migration in the Balkans.{{sfn|Szabo|2002|p=7–36}}

===Gothic theory===
The Gothic theory, which dates back to the late 12th and 13th century work by [[Chronicle of the Priest of Duklja|Priest of Duklja]] and [[Thomas the Archdeacon]],{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=261}}{{sfn|Džino|2010|p=20}} without excluding that some Gothic segments could survive the collapse of [[Ostrogothic Kingdom|Gothic Kingdom]] and were included in Croatian ethnogenesis, is based on almost none concrete evidence to identify Croats with the [[Goths]].{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=261}}{{sfn|Džino|2010|p=20}} In 1102, Croatian Kingdom entered a [[Croatia in the union with Hungary|personal union]] with [[Kingdom of Hungary]]. It is considered that this identification of Croats with Goths is based on a local Croatian [[Trpimirović dynasty|Trpimirović]] dynastic myth from the 11th century, paralleling Hungarian [[Árpád dynasty]]'s myth of originating from the Hunnic leader [[Attila]].{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=261}}{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=22}}

Some scholars like Nada Klaić considered that Thomas the Archdeacon despised Slavs/Croats and that wanted to depreciate them as barbarians with Goths identification, however, until the time of Renaissance the Goths were seen as noble barbarians compared to Huns, Avars, Vandals, Langobards, Magyars and Slavs, and as such he would not identify them with the Goths.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=260}}{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=21-22}} Also, in the Thomas the Archdeacon's work the starting emphasis is on the decadence of people from [[Salona]], and as such scholars consider the emergence of newcomers Goths/Croats was actually seen as a kind of God's scourge for sinful Romans.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=260-261}}{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=21-22}}

Scholars like [[Ludwig Gumplowicz]] and Kerubin Šegvić literally read the medieval works and considered Croats as Goths who were eventually Slavicized, and that the ruling caste was formed from the foreign warrior element.{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=27}}{{sfn|Bartulin|2013|p=117–118}} The idea was argued with the Gothic suffix ''[[wikt:mære|mære]]'' (''mer'', famous) found among the names of Croatian dukes on stone and written inscriptions, as well Slavic suffix ''slav'' (famous), and that ''mer'' eventually was changed with ''mir'' (peace) because the Slavs twisted the interpretation of the names according their language.{{sfn|Tafra|2003|p=16-18}} The ethnonym ''Hrvat'' was derived from the Germanic-Gothic ''Hrôthgutans'', the ''[[hrōþ]]'' (victory, glory) and ''[[Gaut|gutans]]'' (common historical name for the [[Goths]]).{{sfn|Bartulin|2013|p=118}} The Gothic theory, as well as Pan-Slavic during Yugoslavia, was the only supported theory by the regime of [[Independent State of Croatia|NDH]].{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=27}}{{sfn|Džino|2010|p=20}}

===Avar theory===
The Avar, also known as Avar-Bulgarian, Bulgarian or Turkic theory, dates to the late 19th and early 20th century when [[J. B. Bury|John Bagnell Bury]] noted the similarity between Croatian legend of five brothers (and two sisters) with Bulgarian legend of [[Kubrat]]'s five sons.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=259}} He considered that the White Croats' ''Chrobatos'' and [[Bulgars]]' ''Kubrat'' were the same person from the Bulgars ethnic group, as well derived the Croatian title [[Ban (title)|Ban]] from the personal name of Avar khagan [[Bayan I]] and Kubrat's son [[Batbayan]].{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=259}}

The theory was initially developed by Otto Kronsteiner in 1978.{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=27}}{{sfn|Džino|2010|p=21}} He tried to prove that early Croats were an upper caste of [[Avars (Carpathians)|Avar]] origin, which blended with Slavic nobility during the 7th and 8th century and abandoned their Avar language.{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=28}} As arguments for his thesis he considered the [[Tatar language|Tatar]]-[[Bashkir language|Bashkir]] derivation of Croatian ethnonym;{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=28}} that Croats and Avars are almost always mentioned together;{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=28}} distribution of Avarian type of settlements where the Croatian ethnonym was as toponym, ''pagus Crouuati'' in [[Carinthia (state)|Carinthia]] and ''Kraubath'' in [[Styria]];{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=28}} this settlements had Avarian names with suffix ''*-iki'' (''-itji'');{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=28}} the commander of those settlements was Avarian ''Ban'' which name is located in the center of those settlements, ''Faning/Baniče'' < ''Baniki'' in Carinthia, and ''Fahnsdorf < Bansdorf'' in Styria;{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=28}} the Avarian officers titles, besides Mong.-Turk. [[Khagan]], the Kosezes/Kasazes, Ban and [[Župan]].{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=28}} Previously, by some Yugoslavian historians the toponym ''Obrov(ac)'' was also considered of Avar origin,{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=257}} and according to Kronsteiner's claims, which many Nada Klaić accepted, Klaić moved the ancient homeland of White Croats to [[Carantania]].{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=28}}

However, according to [[Peter Štih]] and modern scholars, Kronsteiner arguments were plain assumptions which historians can not objectively accept as evidence.{{sfn|Štih|1995|p=127}} Actually, the etymology derivation is one of many, and is not generally accepted;<ref name="Gluhak">{{citation |first=Alemko |last=Gluhak |author-link=Alemko Gluhak |title=Podrijetlo imena Hrvat |trans-title=The origin of the ethnonym Hrvat |publisher=[[Jezik]] (Croatian Philological Society) |location=Zagreb |year=1990 |url=http://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=116509&lang=en |language=Croatian |pages=131–133}}</ref><ref name="Matasovic">{{citation |first=Ranko |last=Matasović |author-link=Ranko Matasović |title=Poredbenopovijesna gramatika hrvatskoga jezika |trans-title=A Comparative and Historical Grammar of Croatian |publisher=[[Matica hrvatska]] |location=Zagreb |year=2008 |isbn=978-953-150-840-7 |language=Croatian |pages=44}}</ref> the Croats are mentioned along the Avars only in the Constantine VII's work, but always as enemies of the Avars, who destroyed and expelled their authority from Dalmatia;{{sfn|Štih|1995|p=128}} those settlements had widespread Slavic suffix ''ići'', the settlements do not have the semicircular Avar type arrangement, and the ''Ban's'' settlements could not be his seat as are very small and are not found on any important crossroad or geographical location;{{sfn|Štih|1995|p=130}} the titles origin and derivation are unsolved, and they are not found among Avars and Avar language;{{sfn|Štih|1995|p=130}}{{sfn|Živković|2012|p=144, 145}} toponyms with root ''Obrov'' derive from South Slavic verb "obrovati" (to dig a [[trench]]) and are mostly of later date (from the 14th century).{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=257}}

The theory was further developed by [[Walter Pohl]].{{sfn|Džino|2010|p=20–21, 47}} He noted the difference between infantry-agricultural (Slavic) and cavalry-nomadic (Avar) tradition, but did not negate that sometimes the situation was exactly the opposite, and often sources did not differentiate Slavs and Avars.{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=28-29}}{{sfn|Pohl|1995|p=88-90}} He initially shared the Bury's opinion on the Kubrat's and Chrobatos' name and legends, and the mention of two sisters interpreted as additional elements which joined the alliance "by the maternal line", and noted that the symbolism of the number seven is often encountered in the [[Eurasian nomads|steppe peoples]].{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=29}} Pohl noted that the Kronsteiner's merit was that, instead of the previously usual "ethnic" ethnogenesis, he proposed a "social" one.{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=29}} As such, Croatian name would not be an ethnonym, but a social designation for a group of elite warriors of diverse origin which ruled over the conquered Slavic population on the [[Avar Khaganate]]'s boundary,{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=29}}{{sfn|Džino|2010|p=20–21, 47}} the designation eventually becoming an ethnonym{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=29}} imposed to the Slavic groups.{{sfn|Džino|2010|p=21, 47}} The assertion about the boundary is only partly true because although the Croats were mentioned on the line of Khaganate they were mostly outside and not inside the boundaries.{{sfn|Budak|2018|pp=101}} He did not support Kronstenier's derivation, nor consider the etymology important as it is impossible to establish the ethnic origin of "original Croats", ''i.e.'' the social categories which carried the title of "Hrvat".{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=29}}

Lately, a more pro-Turkic (as White [[Onogurs|Oghurs]]) thesis was given by Osman Karatay.{{sfn|Heršak, Silić|2002|p=213}} This theory is not taken into consideration, as it frequently disregarded existing historiographical scholarship.{{sfn|Džino|2010|p=22}} It also considered the Turkic origin of Bosnian polity, and this was viewed as popularisation of links between [[Bosnian Muslims]] with [[Turkey]].{{sfn|Džino|2010|p=22}}

However, the origin and ethnogenesis of Eurasian Avars and their language still remains completely unresolved, and probably beside Slavs also included components and influence from other ethnic groups like [[Eurasian Steppe]]-Iranians, being a heterogeneous tribal community by which both Avar and Iranian theory are not mutually exclusive.{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=29}}

===Iranian theory===
The Iranian, also known as Iranian-Caucasian theory, dates to the 1797 and the doctoral dissertation by [[Josip Mikoczy-Blumenthal]] who, as the dissertation mysteriously disappeared in 1918 and was preserved only a short review, considered that Croats originated from [[Sarmatians]] who were  descending from [[Medes]] in North-Western Iran.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stagličić |first=Ivan |date=27 November 2008 |title=Ideja o iranskom podrijetlu traje preko dvjesto godina |trans-title=Idea about Iranian theory lasts over two hundred years |url=http://www.zadarskilist.hr/clanci/27112008/ideja-o-iranskom-podrijetlu-traje-preko-dvjesto-godina |language=Croatian |newspaper=[[Zadarski list]] |location=Zadar |access-date=15 March 2015}}</ref> In 1853 were discovered the two [[Tanais Tablets]].<ref name="Tanais">{{citation |first=Ante |last=Škegro |title=Two Public Inscriptions from the Greek Colony of Tanais at the Mouth of the Don River on the Sea of Azov |publisher=Review of Croatian History |volume=I |issue=1 |year=2005 |url=http://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=35393&lang=en |pages=9, 15, 21–22, 24}}</ref> They are written in Greek, and were founded in the Greek colony of [[Tanais]] in the late 2nd and early 3rd century AD, at the time when the colony was surrounded by Sarmatians.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=262}}{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=26}} On the larger inscription is written ''the father of the devotional assembly Horouathon'' and ''the son of Horoathu'', while on the smaller inscription ''Horoathos, the son of Sandarz, the archons of the Tanaisians'',<ref name="Tanais"/> which resembles the usual variation of Croathian ethnonym ''Hrvat'' - ''Horvat''.<ref name="Tanais"/> It should be noted that some scholars use these tablets only to explain the etymology, and not necessarily the ethnogenesis.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=260}}

The Iranian theory entered the historical science from three, initially independent ways, from historical-philological, art history, and religion history, in the first half of the 20th century.{{sfn|Košćak|1995|p=110}} The last two were supported by art historian scholars (Luka Jelić, [[Josef Strzygowski]], Ugo Monneret de Villard),{{sfn|Košćak|1995|p=111-112}} and religion historian scholars (Johann Peisker, Milan Šufflay, Ivo Pilar).{{sfn|Košćak|1995|p=112}} The Slavic-Iranian cultural interrelation was pointed out by modern ethnologists, like Marijana Gušić who in the ritual [[Spring procession of Ljelje/Kraljice|Ljelje]] noticed the influence from [[Pontus (region)|Pontic]]-[[Caucasus|Caucasian]]-Iranian sphere,<ref>{{citation |first=Ivan |last=Lozica |title=Kraljice u Akademiji |trans-title=Kraljice [Queens] in Academy |publisher=Narodna umjetnost: Croatian Journal of Ethnology and Folklore Research |volume=37 |issue=2 |year=2000 |url=http://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=53175&lang=en |pages=69}}</ref>{{sfn|Košćak|1995|p=114}} Branimir Gušić,{{sfn|Košćak|1995|p=114}} and archeologists [[Zdenko Vinski]] and Ksenija Vinski-Gasparini.{{sfn|Košćak|1995|p=114-115}} However, the cultural and artistic indicators of Iranian origin, including indications in the religious sphere, is somehow difficult to determine.{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=26}} It is mostly [[Sassanian Empire|Sassanian]] (224-651 AD) influences that were felt in the steppe regions.{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=26}}

The first scholar who connected the tablets names with Croatian ethnonym was A. L. Pogodin in 1902.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=263}}{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=26}} First who considered such a thesis and Iranian origin was [[Konstantin Josef Jireček]] in 1911.{{sfn|Košćak|1995|p=110}} Ten years later, Al. I. Sobolevski gave the first systematic theory about the Iranian origin which until today did not change in basic lines.{{sfn|Košćak|1995|p=110}} In the same year, independently [[Fran Ramovš]], with reference to the Iranian interpretation of the name Horoathos by [[Max Vasmer]], concluded that the early Croats were one of the Sarmatian tribes which during the great migration advanced along the outer edge of Carpathians ([[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]]) to the Vistula and [[Elbe]] rivers.{{sfn|Košćak|1995|p=110}} The almost final, and more in detail picture was given by Slovenian academic Ljudmil Hauptmann in 1935.{{sfn|Košćak|1995|p=110}} He considered that Iranian Croats, after the Huns invasion around 370 when the Huns crossed the [[Volga]] river and attacked the Iranian [[Alans]] at the [[Don River (Russia)|Don]] river, abandoned their initial Sarmatian lands and arrived among the Slavs at the wast lands north of Carpathians, where they gradually Slavicized.{{sfn|Košćak|1995|p=111}} There they belonged to the [[Antes people|Antes]] tribal polity until the Antes were attacked by the Avars in 560, and the polity was finally destroyed 602 by the same Avars.{{sfn|Košćak|1995|p=111}} The thesis was subsequently supported by [[Francis Dvornik]], [[George Vernadsky]], [[Roman Jakobson]], [[Tadeusz Sulimirski]], and [[Oleg Trubachyov]].{{sfn|Košćak|1995|p=112-113}} In 1985, [[Omeljan Pritsak]] considered early Croats a clan of Alan-Iranian origin which during the "Avarian pax" had frontiersman-merchant social role.{{sfn|Košćak|1995|p=113}}

The personal names on the Tanais Tablets are considered as a prototype of a certain ethnonym of a Sarmatian tribe those persons did descend from,{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=262}}<ref name="Gluhak"/> and as well today is generally accepted that the Croatian name is of Iranian origin and that can be traced to the Tanais Tablets.<ref name="Gluhak"/><ref name="Matasovic"/> However, the etymology itself is not enough strong evidence.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=262}} The theory is further explained with the Avar's destruction of Antes tribal polity in 602, and that the early Croats migration and subsequent war with Avars in Dalmatia (during the reign of Heraclius 610-641) can be seen as a continuation of the war between Antes and Avars.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=263}} That the early Croats marked the [[Cardinal direction#Cardinal directions in world cultures|cardinal directions]] with colors, hence White Croats and White Croatia (Western) and [[Red Croatia]] (Southern),{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=263}} but the cardinal color designation, in general, indicates remnants of the widespread steppe peoples tradition.{{sfn|Katičić|1999|p=8-16}} The heterogeneous composition of the Croatian legend in which are unusually mentioned two women leaders ''Touga'' and ''Bouga'', which indicates to what the actual archaeological findings confirmed - the existence of "warrior women" known as [[Amazons]] among the Sarmatians and Scythians.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=263}} As such, Trubachyov tried to explain the original proto-type of the ethnonym from adjectives ''*xar-va(n)t'' (feminine, rich in women), which derives from the etymology of Sarmatians, the [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan]] ''*sar-ma(n)t'' (feminine), in both [[Indo-Iranian languages|Indo-Iran]] adjective suffix ''-ma(n)t/wa(n)t'', and Indo-Aryan and Indo-Iranian word ''*sar-'' (woman), which in Iranian gives ''*har''.<ref name="Gluhak"/>

Another interpretation was given by the scholar Jevgenij Paščenko; he considered that the Croats were a heterogeneous group of people belonging to the [[Chernyakhov culture]], a poly-ethnic cultural mélange of mostly Slavs and Sarmatians, but also Goths, [[Getae]] and [[Dacians]].{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=46-48}} There was happening an interrelation between Slavic and Iranian language and culture, seen for example in the toponymy.{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=46-48}} As such, under the ethnonym ''Hrvati'' should not be necessary seen a specific or even homogeneous tribe, yet archaic religion and mythology of a heterogeneous group of people of Iranian origin or influence who worshiped the [[solar deity]] [[Hors]], from which possibly originates the Croatian ethnonym.{{sfn|Paščenko|2006|p=67-82, 109-111}}

The another known more radical thesis of the Iranian theory was by [[Stjepan Krizin Sakač]], who although gave insights on some issues, tried to follow the Croatian ethnonym as far the region [[Arachosia]] (''Harahvaiti'', ''Harauvatiš'') and its people (''Harahuvatiya'') of the [[Achaemenid Empire]] (550–330 BCE).{{sfn|Budak|2018|pp=98–99}}{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=263}}{{sfn|Katičić|1999|p=11-12}} However, although the suggestive similarity, it is etymologically incorrect.{{sfn|Katičić|1999|p=12}} There were many supporters of the thesis and further tried to develop it, but the actual arguments are considered far-fetched and unscientific.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=263}}{{sfn|Košćak|1995|p=112}}{{sfn|Katičić|1999|p=15}}

==Anthropological and genetic studies==
===Anthropology===
Anthropologically, the [[Craniometry|craniometrical]] measurements made on the contemporary Croatian population of the city of Zagreb showed it is predominantly [[Cephalic index#Indices|dolichocephalic]], more specifically [[Cephalic index#Indices|mesocephalia]] and leptoprosopia prevail in South Dalmatia, and [[brachycephaly]] and euryprosopy in Central Croatia.<ref>{{citation |author=Đ. Grbeša |date=2007 |title=Craniofacial Characteristics of Croatian and Syrian Populations |url=http://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=42706&lang=en |journal=Collegium Antropologicum |volume=31 |issue=4 |pages=1121–1125 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> According to the 1998-2004 craniometric study of medieval Central European archaeological sites, four Dalmatian and two Bosnian sites clustered with [[Poland|Polish]] sites, two Continental Croatia (Avaro-Slav) sites were classified into the cluster of Hungarian sites west of the Danube, while the two sites from the [[Bijelo Brdo culture]] were into the cluster of Slav sites from [[Austria]], the [[Czech Republic]], and [[Slovenia]]. Comparison to the Scythian-Sarmatian sites did not reveal significant similarity in cranial morphology, nor was supported the idea of the Avar frontiersmen. The results indicate that the nucleus of the early Croat state in Dalmatia was of Slavic ancestry, which arrived from the area somewhere in Poland probably along the direct route [[Nitra]]-[[Zalaszabar]]-[[Nin, Croatia|Nin]], and gradually expanded into the continental hinterland of Bosnia and Herzegovina by the 10th century, however, by the end of the 11th century did not in Eastern Slavonia.<ref>{{citation |author=M. Šlaus |date=1998 |title=Craniometric relationships of medieval Central European populations: Implications for Croat ethnogenesis |url=https://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=137261&lang=en |journal=Starohrvatska prosvjeta |volume=3 |issue=25 |pages=81–107}}</ref><ref>{{citation |author=M. Šlaus |date=2000 |title=Kraniometrijska analiza srednjovjekovnih nalazišta središnje Europe: Novi dokazi o ekspanziji hrvatskih populacija tijekom 10. do 13. stoljeća |url=https://hrcak.srce.hr/5505?lang=en |journal=Opuscula Archaeologica: Papers of the Department of Archaeology |volume=23–24 |issue=1 |pages=273–284}}</ref><ref>{{citation |author=M. Šlaus |date=2004 |title=Craniometric relationships among medieval Central European populations: implications for Croat migration and expansion. |pmid=15311416 |journal=Croatian medical journal |volume=45 |issue=4 |pages=434–444 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> The 2015 study of medieval skeletal remains in [[Šopot]] (14th-15th century) and [[Ostrovica, Croatia|Ostrovica]] (9th century) found out they cluster with other Dalmatian sites as well Polish sites, concluding that "PCA showed that all Eastern Adriatic coast sites were closely related in cranial morphology, and thus, most likely had similar biological makeup".{{sfn|Bašić et al.|2015}}

===Population genetics===
{{main|Genetic studies on Croats}}
[[Genetics|Genetically]], on the [[Y chromosome]] line, a majority (>85%) of male Croats from Croatia belong to one of the three major European Y-DNA [[haplogroup]]s - [[Haplogroup I (Y-DNA)|I]] (38%{{sfn|Barać et al.|2003}}{{sfn|Rootsi et al.|2004}}{{sfn|Peričić et al.|2005}}-44%{{sfn|Battaglia et al.|2008}}), [[Haplogroup R1a (Y-DNA)|R1a]] (27%{{sfn|Battaglia et al.|2008}}-34%{{sfn|Barać et al.|2003}}{{sfn|Rootsi et al.|2004}}{{sfn|Peričić et al.|2005}}) and [[Haplogroup R1b (Y-DNA)|R1b]] (12.4%{{sfn|Battaglia et al.|2008}}-15%{{sfn|Barać et al.|2003}}{{sfn|Rootsi et al.|2004}}{{sfn|Peričić et al.|2005}}), while a minority (>15%) mostly belongs to haplogroup [[Haplogroup E (Y-DNA)|E]] (9%{{sfn|Battaglia et al.|2008}}), and others to haplgroups [[Haplogroup J (Y-DNA)|J]] (4.4%{{sfn|Battaglia et al.|2008}}), [[Haplogroup N (Y-DNA)|N]] (2%{{sfn|Battaglia et al.|2008}}), and [[Haplogroup G (Y-DNA)|G]] (1%{{sfn|Battaglia et al.|2008}}). Genetically, on the maternal [[X chromosome]] line, a majority (>65%) of female Croats from Croatia (mainland and coast) belong to three of the eleven major European mtDNA haplogroups - [[Haplogroup H (mtDNA)|H]] (45%), [[Haplogroup U (mtDNA)|U]] (17.8-20.8%), [[Haplogroup J (mtDNA)|J]] (3-11%), while a large minority (>35%) belongs to many other smaller haplogroups.{{sfn|Cvjetan et al.|2004}}

The region of modern-day Croatia may have served as a [[Last Glacial Maximum refugia|refugium]] for the northern populations during the [[Last Glacial Maximum|last glacial maximum]] (LGM).{{sfn|Battaglia et al.|2008}} The eastern Adriatic coast was much further south.{{sfn|Rootsi et al.|2004}} The northern and the western parts of that sea were steppes and plains, while the modern Croatian islands (rich in Paleolithic archeological sites) were hills and mountains.{{sfn|Rootsi et al.|2004}}{{sfn|Battaglia et al.|2008}} The region had a specific role in the structuring of European, and particularly among Slavic, paternal genetic heritage, characterized by the predominance of R1a and I, and scarcity of E lineages.{{sfn|Peričić et al.|2005}} However, DNA can not be completely connected and used as the evidence for a specific ethnic component, but only as an indication.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=264}}

